Prologue
“Please!” Queen Elwynn begged, “Don't send her away! She's just a child!” The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with royal advisors standing beside him. The queen had given birth to a girl. At the thought of this, the Ice King couldn't help but furrow his brow.
The infant girl looked like her mother: with pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, and a few strands of blue hair. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only sons before.
“You've got two options: either kill the child or leave her in the wilderness. Elwynn, this is your punishment.” He spoke her name with malice, as if it were poison. He always was like that.
The Kingdom of Frost wasn't always a kingdom. It was once divided into two parts: the north and the south. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom filled with magical powers. Due to the north's greed, the two kingdoms started an endless war, until the south proposed a truce.
When the South had fallen into despair, members of the royal family were willing to pay any price to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed that the only princess be married to the North and become the queen of the North, bearing a son as the future king. After that, the South would merge with the North and establish a unified kingdom. The North accepted this proposal, and Princess Elwyn was married to Prince Arcturus.
“Please, my king, for the sake of my child's safety, you can do anything to me – lock me up, exile me, even kill me,” Princess Elwyn begged, hugging her child tightly.
The Ice King looked down at the queen, his eyes filled with disgust. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would have a shred of pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him in his most desperate times, and borne him children.
“Alright. The child can stay in the palace,” the Ice King said, and Princess Elwyn breathed a sigh of relief. “But,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisors and Princess Elwyn both showed shocked expressions. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. “Yes, my king,” she bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to a vacant room in Elwynn. After that, he ordered the guards to bring Elwynn to the public execution ground.
When the guards were escorting her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen, who was also the kindest queen, about to be executed and felt very angry. Some people cried, some people shouted and tried to attack the guards, and some people wondered why this was happening; but they all had the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they treating her this way?"
When Elwynn approached the wooden pillar, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of the flames. The former queen Elwynn would be burned alive. No one should be executed by fire, even if they are criminals. In the Ice Kingdom, execution by fire is the most cruel punishment.
Elwyn was bound to a wooden pillar, and the king began to tell how the queen had betrayed them all. People from the Frost Kingdom refused to believe and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the pillar, and a tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Carly, live on!" This was the end of Elwyn's life as a queen.
The hall was silent.
In the cold palace's south wing, from the leftmost room, an endless "ticking" sound came. Past servants were always curious about what was inside, but they were too afraid to get close. The maids walked around the hall, whispering to each other, spreading various rumors. Some people believed that the Ice King's deceased wife, Elwyn, lived in this room, waiting to be released.
They were completely wrong. Avery thought about this as he walked towards the south wing, while the servants walked along the wall, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there are many rumors about her, because she's the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you in there?" Avery whispered to the complex door, which was decorated with snowflakes and crown patterns, symbolizing the royal family.
He didn't know if she would let him in this time, which was different from before. I still have the bruises from last time. Avery remembered this and couldn't help but laugh. At that time, Carly threw a book at him, but immediately apologized when she saw who it was.
A soft sound came from the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere else, and just stayed there.
"Can I come in?" Avery asked, and he couldn't forget the consequences of his last time uninvited entry.
The room made another faint sound. It seemed to be saying, "Come in." Avery felt a chill run down his spine, unsure if it was from the cold or the voice. Despite being there for many years, whenever he heard sounds coming from the room, Avery still found it a bit strange.
"I'm in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. From a normal person's perspective, the scene in the room was quite unusual, but it was also to be expected. The room was filled with paper. Books were scattered all over the floor, the desk was broken, and there were many ice sculptures in the room. There was no window, and there was almost no light. The room was also colder than other parts of the palace (which explained a lot). The room looked like it had been attacked by a blizzard, with everything in disarray.
The girl in the room was curled up on the bed, wrapped in a blanket, reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked, sitting down on the edge of Carly's bed.
